<li id="cite_note-Economist1-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Economist1_13-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.economist.com/finance/displayStory.cfm?story_id=5246700" class="external text" title="http://www.economist.com/finance/displayStory.cfm?story_id=5246700" rel="nofollow">"Abortion, crime and econometrics"</a>. The Economist. <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2005-12-01"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="12-01"><a href="/wiki/December_1" title="December 1">December 1</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2005" title="2005">2005</a></span><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.economist.com/finance/displayStory.cfm?story_id=5246700" class="external free" title="http://www.economist.com/finance/displayStory.cfm?story_id=5246700" rel="nofollow">http://www.economist.com/finance/displayStory.cfm?story_id=5246700</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-07-10</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Abortion%2C+crime+and+econometrics&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.date=%5B%5BDecember+1%5D%5D%2C+%5B%5B2005%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=The+Economist&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.economist.com%2Ffinance%2FdisplayStory.cfm%3Fstory_id%3D5246700&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Fixing_Broken_Windows"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-SAILER1-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-SAILER1_14-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFSailer">Sailer, Steve (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2005-05-09"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="05-09"><a href="/wiki/May_9" title="May 9">May 9</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2005" title="2005">2005</a></span>). <a href="http://amconmag.com/2005_05_09/feature.html" class="external text" title="http://amconmag.com/2005_05_09/feature.html" rel="nofollow">"Pre-emptive Executions?: The notion that legalizing abortion drives down crime rates is logically flawed and morally repugnant"</a>. The American Conservative<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://amconmag.com/2005_05_09/feature.html" class="external free" title="http://amconmag.com/2005_05_09/feature.html" rel="nofollow">http://amconmag.com/2005_05_09/feature.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-07-10</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Pre-emptive+Executions%3F%3A++The+notion+that+legalizing+abortion+drives+down+crime+rates+is+logically+flawed+and+morally+repugnant&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Sailer&amp;rft.aufirst=Steve&amp;rft.au=Sailer%2C+Steve&amp;rft.date=%5B%5BMay+9%5D%5D%2C+%5B%5B2005%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=The+American+Conservative&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Famconmag.com%2F2005_05_09%2Ffeature.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Fixing_Broken_Windows"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFHarcourtLudwig.2C_Jens2006">Harcourt, Bernard E.; Ludwig, Jens (2006). "<a href="http://ssrn.com/abstract=743284" class="external text" title="http://ssrn.com/abstract=743284" rel="nofollow">Broken Windows: New Evidence from New York City and a Five-City Social Experiment</a>". <i>University of Chicago Law Review</i> <b>73</b><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://ssrn.com/abstract=743284" class="external free" title="http://ssrn.com/abstract=743284" rel="nofollow">http://ssrn.com/abstract=743284</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Broken+Windows%3A+New+Evidence+from+New+York+City+and+a+Five-City+Social+Experiment&amp;rft.jtitle=University+of+Chicago+Law+Review&amp;rft.aulast=Harcourt&amp;rft.aufirst=Bernard+E.&amp;rft.au=Harcourt%2C+Bernard+E.&amp;rft.au=Ludwig%2C+Jens&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.volume=73&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fssrn.com%2Fabstract%3D743284&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Fixing_Broken_Windows"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
</div>
<p><a name="Further_reading" id="Further_reading"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Fixing_Broken_Windows&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Further reading">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Further reading</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Eli B. Silverman. <i>NYPD Battles Crime: Innovative Strategies in Policing</i>. <a href="/wiki/Northeastern_University_(Boston,_Massachusetts)" title="Northeastern University (Boston, Massachusetts)" class="mw-redirect">Northeastern University</a> Press, 1999.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/William_J._Bratton" title="William J. Bratton">William J. Bratton</a>. <i>Turnaround: How America's Top Cop Reversed the Crime Epidemic</i>. <a href="/wiki/Random_House" title="Random House">Random House</a>, 1998.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Wesley G. Skogan. <i>Disorder and Decline: Crime and the Spiral of Decay in American Neighborhoods</i>. University of California Press, 1990.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Bernard E. Harcourt. "Illusion of Order: The False Promise of Broken Windows Policing". Harvard University Press 2001.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>John E. Eck &amp; Edward R. Maguire, "Have Changes in Policing Reduced Violent Crime?" in Alfred Blumstein and Joel Wallman, eds. <i>The Crime Drop in America, rev. ed.</i> <a href="/wiki/Cambridge_University_Press" title="Cambridge University Press">Cambridge University Press</a>, 2006.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Malcolm_Gladwell" title="Malcolm Gladwell">Malcolm Gladwell</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/The_Tipping_Point_(book)" title="The Tipping Point (book)" class="mw-redirect">The Tipping Point: How Little Things Can Make a Big Difference</a></i>. Back Bay Books, 2002. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0316346624" class="internal">ISBN 0-316-34662-4</a></li>
</ul>
<p><a name="External_links" id="External_links"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Fixing_Broken_Windows&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">External links</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://legalaffairs.org/webexclusive/debateclub_brokenwindows1005.msp" class="external text" title="http://legalaffairs.org/webexclusive/debateclub_brokenwindows1005.msp" rel="nofollow"><i>Legal Affairs</i> magazine</a> - a review of the criticisms of the broken windows theory.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.cjcj.org/files/shattering.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.cjcj.org/files/shattering.pdf" rel="nofollow">Shattering "Broken Windows": An Analysis of San Francisco's Alternative Crime Policies.</a> - An Article by <i>Center on Juvenile and Criminal Justice</i> detailing crime reduction in San Francisco achieved via alternative crime policies.</li>
<li><a href="http://blogcritics.org/archives/2006/09/26/221035.php" class="external text" title="http://blogcritics.org/archives/2006/09/26/221035.php" rel="nofollow">A critique of the role of the police in reducing crime rates</a></li>
</ul>


